<meta name="twitter:description" content="FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASECONTACT: media@aclu.orgNEW YORK â With the goal of mapping peopleâs social relationships, the National Security Agency is secretly collecting information on Americans from a previously unknown array of public and commercial sources, according to a report today from The New York Times. The data sources include âbank codes, insurance information, Facebook profiles, passenger manifests, voter registration rolls and GPS location information, as well as property records and unspecified tax data,â the article said.American Civil Liberties Union Deputy Legal Director Jameel Jaffer had this reaction: This report confirms what whistleblowers have been saying for years: the NSA has been monitoring virtually every aspect of Americans&#039; lives â their communications, their associations, even their locations. The NSA apparently believes it can conduct this surveillance because 30 years ago the Supreme Court upheld the governmentâs warrantless collection of basic information about a criminal suspect&#039;s telephone calls over the course of a single day. But the claim that this narrow case from the analog era authorizes the mass surveillance of hundreds of millions of Americans is outlandish. That the NSAâs surveillance activities rest on so flimsy a foundation is further evidence that our intelligence-oversight system is utterly broken.More information on NSA spying is at:aclu.org/nsa-surveillance" />
